RAS: Looks like a good value play on some metrics I use.

Great profit margins. However, you pay for that because the p/sales ratio is
very high. 12% div. yield. Stock's near its three year or longer low. OTOH,
stock seems to be range-bound for the past few years. (So maybe it's the
dividend yield that the attraction.) Price/bk seems okay for a buy (at 1.17).
OTOH, the stock's traded on average in some years at below stated book value.

I don't understand the benefit to investors why the company would buy back 3M
of 63M shares outstanding, and use convertible notes to do it. Notes so far
from conversion that it won't be reflected in "fully diluted shares", so some
financial numbers will look better with the fewer listed outstanding shares? I
see where d/e is 8.7/1, according to Yahoo; perhaps that's okay, perhaps not.
D/e seems to have jumped up enormously in past year.

The thing of it is though, is how many professional value players are in this
stock, according to latest Yahoo. Assuming they're still in -- who knows what
they've done with the onset now of these subprime issues -- we have Marty
Whitman, Leon Cooperman, Munder, Excelsior Restructuring...some of the best of
the best. Assuming one or more of these folks has looked closely at what
they've bought (and are still in it), I'd say RAS might be a buy for someone
who wants to make a value bet where the outcome is not so clear unless you
really know what you own.

I'll consider a few shares, but I'm not so sure I have the fortitude to hold on
to this one in these times.
